        "body": "Verse 2 supplies the *why* of the entire psalm, and it is the only verse that does. Every imperative in vv.3-5 rests on these two grounds; every breathing creature in v.6 praises for these two reasons. The verse is doctrinally compact: praise Him **for His mighty deeds** (*gevurotav*) and **according to His excellent greatness** (*rov gudlo*).\n\n*Gevurot* — mighty deeds, acts of power — names what God has *done*. The plural points to the cumulative testimony of Israel's history: the exodus from Egypt, the parting of the Red Sea, the conquest of Canaan, the Davidic victories, the return from exile, and behind them all the original mighty deed of creation itself. The Psalter has spent 149 prior psalms rehearsing these deeds; Psalm 150 now distills them into a single word. To praise God for His *gevurot* is to praise Him as the God who acts in history — not the deistic absent watchmaker, not the mystical impersonal force, but the *Lord who works wonders* (Psalm 77:14).\n\n*Godel* — greatness, magnitude, majesty — names what God *is*. Where *gevurot* points to His acts, *godel* points to His being. The modifier *rov* (abundance, much, surpassing) intensifies it: the *abundance of His greatness*, the *surpassing greatness*. This is the intrinsic majesty of God's person, independent of any act He performs. Even if (impossibly) God had created nothing and redeemed no one, He would still merit praise as *El* — the great God, the holy and majestic One.\n\nThese two grounds — works and being — are the classical apologetic for praise. Strip away the deeds and you have empty mysticism (worshiping a God who doesn't act). Strip away the being and you have rationalist gratitude (thanking a God whose person doesn't matter once the gifts are received). Spurgeon: *His greatness is excellent because it is so genuine, so vast, so unique, so glorious.* The believer praises God both for what He has done in saving him and for who He is in Himself, eternally and unchangeably.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Gevurot* (mighty deeds) — plural of *gevurah*, acts of power; the word that names David's *mighty men* (2 Samuel 23:8) and YHWH's saving acts (Deuteronomy 3:24). *Godel* (greatness) — the intrinsic magnitude of God's person; *rov* (abundance) intensifies it: the surpassing greatness."
