        "title": "The means of praise — the full Levitical orchestra",
        "range": "150:3-5",
        "excerpt": "Praise Him with trumpet sound; Praise Him with harp and lyre. Praise Him with timbrel and dancing; Praise Him with stringed instruments and pipe. Praise Him with loud cymbals; Praise Him with resounding cymbals.",
        "body": "Three verses, eight references to instruments and one to dancing, organized as a deliberate crescendo. Verse 3 opens with the **trumpet** (*shophar*) — the ram's-horn that announces theophany at Sinai (Exodus 19:16, 19), sounds the jubilee (Leviticus 25:9), and rallies Israel for assembly and war (Numbers 10; Joshua 6:4-5). It heads the orchestra because it is the instrument of summons. Paired with it are the **harp** (*nevel*) and the **lyre** (*kinnor*) — the canonical stringed instruments of Levitical temple worship (1 Chronicles 15:16, 20-21) and David's own instrument (1 Samuel 16:23). Verse 3 names the priestly summons-instrument and the royal-Levitical strings together: priest and king joined in worship.\n\nVerse 4 adds embodied and pastoral instruments: **timbrel** (*toph*) and **dancing** (*machol*). *Toph* is the hand-drum carried by Miriam after the Red Sea (Exodus 15:20) and by the women greeting David's victories (1 Samuel 18:6) — the instrument of *victory celebration*. *Machol* is the round-dance, the embodied response that David himself performed before the ark (2 Samuel 6:14). Together they name **worship that includes the body**. Then **strings** (*minnim*) and **pipe** (*ugav*) round out the verse — the *ugav* being one of Scripture's oldest named instruments (Genesis 4:21), the wind-instrument balancing the strings.\n\nVerse 5 climaxes the crescendo with **cymbals** (*tsiltsal*) named twice, each with a different intensifying adjective: *shema* (clashing, sounding) and *teruah* (resounding, shouting). The cymbals were the loudest instruments in the ancient orchestra (1 Chronicles 15:19; 16:5). The doubling is not redundancy but emphasis — the percussion climax of the entire Psalter's worship. The volume rises across vv.3-5: horn-summons, strings, drum-and-dance, strings-and-pipe, and finally cymbal-clash twice over.\n\nThe list is exhaustive of *categories*, not of individual instruments: wind (horn, pipe), string (harp, lyre, *minnim*), percussion (timbrel, cymbals), and **body** (dancing). Every faculty of human music-making is summoned. This raised a question for the Reformers — does this license instruments in new-covenant worship, or does the move from temple to gathered church silence the orchestra? Calvin held the latter; the Old Testament instruments were part of the *paedagogy* of the temple, a shadow whose substance is the voice of the redeemed in Christ. The Reformed regulative principle has historically taken Calvin's line; many evangelical traditions have not. What is *not* disputed: every tradition reading Psalm 150 must reckon with its **fullness, embodiedness, and volume**. The Psalter's final word on worship is not restraint.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shophar* (horn) — the ram's-horn of theophany and assembly. *Nevel* (harp) and *kinnor* (lyre) — the Levitical and Davidic stringed instruments. *Toph* (timbrel) — the hand-drum of victory celebration. *Machol* (dancing) — the round-dance; *minnim* (strings) and *ugav* (pipe) — additional string and wind. *Tsiltsal* (cymbals) — metal percussion, named twice with *shema* (clashing) and *teruah* (resounding) intensifying."
