        "title": "The scope of praise — every breathing thing",
        "range": "150:6",
        "excerpt": "Let everything that has breath praise the LORD. Praise the LORD!",
        "body": "The final verse widens the summons to its absolute limit. *Kol haneshamah tehallel Yah* — *let every breath praise Yah*. The word *neshamah* is the breath-of-life of Genesis 2:7, when God *breathed* (*nshm*) into the man's nostrils and the man became a living being. To name every *neshamah*-possessor as a praise-giver is to make a theological claim: the breath God gave is **owed back to Him in praise**. Job 33:4 makes the same connection: *the Spirit of God has made me, and the breath* (*neshamah*) *of the Almighty gives me life*.\n\nThe scope is universal. Every breathing creature, without exception. The Psalter that began in Psalm 1 with one solitary man meditating on the law day and night ends with every breathing creature in the cosmos joining one chorus. The trajectory is intentional — Israel's prayer book opens with individual piety and closes with universal doxology. The particular has become the cosmic; the temple has spilled into all creation; the Levitical orchestra has been joined by every set of lungs.\n\nThis anticipates the canonical climax of Revelation 5:13: *every created thing which is in heaven and on the earth and under the earth and on the sea, and all things in them, I heard saying, 'To Him who sits on the throne, and to the Lamb, be blessing and honor and glory and dominion forever and ever.'* John's vision is what Psalm 150:6 looks like when it is finally fulfilled — the universal summons answered universally. The believer reading Psalm 150 reads his own eschatological vocation.\n\nThe psalm ends as it began: *Hallelujah*. Thirteen times in six verses the verb *halal* has been hammered. The Psalter ends not in argument, not in petition, not in lament, but in pure acclamation. Lament has been answered, sin has been forgiven, enemies have been silenced — what remains, eternally, is praise. Jonathan Edwards saw in this the foretaste of heaven's unending occupation: the redeemed will not exhaust this single vocation through eternity because its object is infinite. As long as God is God, praise will be the saint's eternal work.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kol haneshamah* (every breath / everything that has breath) uses *neshamah*, the same word for the breath God breathed into Adam in Genesis 2:7. The verb *tehallel* is the jussive — *let* it praise — a hortatory summons, not a description."
